\section*{APPENDIX B. The fractional cell kill law as a Michaelis-Menten kinetics} \label{app:foobar}

The fractional cell kill law in Eq.~\eqref{eq:8} can be derived from the Michaelis-Menten kinetics \citep{micamen,mimen} assuming that the rate constants of the reaction depend on the enzyme concentration. During the process of lysis, the effector cells $E$ bound to the tumor cells $T$ forming complexes $C$, and dead tumor cells $T^{*}$ result from this interaction. Therefore, the tumor cells play the role of the substrate and the effector cells act as the enzyme. This cellular reaction can be written in the form

Once a tumor cell is induced to apoptosis it can not resurrect, so we must set $k_{-2}=0$. Generally, also the backward reaction represented by $k_{-1}$ should be disregarded, since after tumor cell recognition and complex formation, destruction proceeds. However, we keep this term for reasons explained bellow. 

Assuming that the law of mass action holds, the system of differential equations governing the reactions is
\begin{eqnarray}
&\dfrac{d [E]}{d t}&=-k_{1}[E][T]+(k_{-1}+k_{2})[C] \label{eq:b2}\bigskip\\
&\dfrac{d [T]}{d t}&=-k_{1}[E][T]+k_{-1}[C] \label{eq:b3}\bigskip\\
&\dfrac{d [C]}{d t}&=k_{1}[E][T]-(k_{-1}+k_{2})[C] \label{eq:b4}\bigskip\\
&\dfrac{d [T^{*}]}{d t}&=k_{2}[C]. \label{eq:b5}
\end{eqnarray}


